article.description: Lindsay Whalen scored 23 points and had 11 assists as No. 9 Minnesota beat Iowa 94-65 on Sunday.
article.headline: Whalen totals 23 points, 11 assists
article.linkText: Whalen's double-double leads Gophers past Iowa
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Lindsay Whalen keeps coming up short of her
first triple-double.

	   Whalen had 23 points, 11 assists and nine rebounds as Minnesota  (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP) beat struggling Iowa 94-65 on Sunday. In Thursday's win over
Illinois, Whalen had 21 points, 12 rebounds and eight assists.

	   "I was a little tired by the end of the game, and I was about
ready to come out,'' Whalen said. "Hopefully we'll get it some
other time.''

	   The Gophers (14-1, 3-1 Big Ten) used a stifling man-to-man
defense to create turnovers that led to easy scoring chances,
soaring to a 30-5 lead.

	   Whalen, Corrin Von Wald and Janel McCarville combined for 69
points as Iowa (8-5, 0-2) was blown out for the third straight time
on the road by a ranked opponent.

	   "The key to the game was the way we started out,'' Minnesota
coach Pam Borton said. "It starts with our defense. We got a lot
of stops, which gives us our transition game, and that's where we
excel and thrive.''

	   Von Wald added a season-high 25 points, while McCarville had 21
points and 14 rebounds.

	   The Hawkeyes did not score a field goal until Becca McCann's
layup with 12:05 remaining in the first half. The loss to Minnesota
completed a dismal road trip in which Iowa lost at No. 4 Kansas
State 103-60 and at No. 16 Penn State 86-52.

	   "We're dealing with a lot of self-confidence issues,''
assistant coach Jan Jensen said while the team and head coach Lisa
Bluder held a closed-door meeting. "Everybody's kind of talking
some things out.''

	   Ten of the 14 players on Iowa's roster are either freshmen or
sophomores.

	   "When you're working with a young team, it's really easy to
lose your confidence,'' Jensen said. "It's going to be really
difficult. We did not lose this game because we're so bad.
Minnesota is a great, great basketball team.''

	   Johanna Solverson scored 19 points to lead Iowa, which missed
nine shots and had six turnovers before scoring its first basket.

	   Iowa's Amber Faulkner scored 11 points, while Tiffany Reedy and
McCann added 10 each.

	   McCarville, last season's Big Ten Freshman of the Year, made her
first start since the season opener in November. Coming back from
hip and toe injuries that have limited her playing time,
McCarville's performance against the Hawkeyes followed up the 23
points and nine rebounds she had against Illinois.

	   Kadidja Andersson added 10 points for Minnesota.
